            "title": "Zwischen Liebesideal und Realismus : Theologische Anthropologie als soziale Ressource bei Reinhold Niebuhr",
            "abstract": "What is there left to say about the human condition after the so-called \u201eend of anthropology\u201c? Never before have conceptions of what it means to be a human being been as diverse and fragmented as in the late modern age \u2013 with severe consequences for democratic discourse and liberal, \u201eWestern\u201c societies as a whole. Examining the work of American theologian Reinhold Niebuhr (1892\u20131971), the book presents new insights into the intersection of anthropological thought and ethical orientation. Niebuhr, motivated by his perception of profound political and social crises in \u201eWestern\u201c societies, develops an innovative, pragmatic and \u201erealistic\u201c type of theological anthropology. His anthropological approach functions as the basis of a much larger endeavor: rescuing Christianity and democracy itself. Reading Niebuhr today opens up a refreshing perspective on current debates on public theology and the so-called \u201ecrisis of democracy\u201c. In this context, the book argues, theological anthropology can be reclaimed as an essential social resource: It offers a comprehensive understanding of human nature both at its best and at its worst, providing the indispensable basis for the survival and vitality of democracy",
